WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.510 --> 00:00:02.780
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Hi everyone.

00:00:02.780 --> 00:00:07.180
My name is Erica Chung and I work in People
Operations and I also work on the @Google

00:00:07.180 --> 00:00:09.010
Talks team in New York.

00:00:09.010 --> 00:00:15.290
And today, it is my great, great pleasure
to introduce Kristi Yamaguchi to Google [phone

00:00:15.290 --> 00:00:16.420
rings in background].

00:00:16.420 --> 00:00:21.990
Kristi, I think you guys all know, but she
is the 1992 Olympic figure skater Champion.

00:00:21.990 --> 00:00:27.090
She's also a winner of a recent season of
"Dancing With the Stars" and she had recently

00:00:27.090 --> 00:00:30.880
added best-selling author to her litany of
accomplishments.

00:00:30.880 --> 00:00:35.710
[giggles] And her book is called "Dream Big,
Little Pig."

00:00:35.710 --> 00:00:41.229
So, we're gonna ask her to actually do a reading
for us today.

00:00:41.229 --> 00:00:45.249
Kristi's also--on a personal note--my childhood
hero.

00:00:45.249 --> 00:00:46.550
So I am absolutely thrilled.

00:00:46.550 --> 00:00:52.309
[audience laughs] I can't tell you how excited
I am to be sitting here right now.

00:00:52.309 --> 00:00:56.969
So, Kristi, I thought we would just start
by talking a little bit about figure skating

00:00:56.969 --> 00:00:57.969
and your journey.

00:00:57.969 --> 00:00:58.969
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: OK.

00:00:58.969 --> 00:01:05.750
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: And I understand that--correct
me if I'm wrong--but I believe you had started

00:01:05.750 --> 00:01:11.110
skating as a form of therapy to correct clubbed
feet.

00:01:11.110 --> 00:01:12.110
Is that true?

00:01:12.110 --> 00:01:18.230
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Well, it did help with
strength and coordination.

00:01:18.230 --> 00:01:26.280
I was born with club feet and was in casts
for the first year or so of my life.

00:01:26.280 --> 00:01:32.090
And then corrective shoes and braces until
maybe two.

00:01:32.090 --> 00:01:36.740
I remember learning to walk with the brace
in-between my feet [chuckles].

00:01:36.740 --> 00:01:40.260
But those corrections were pretty much done
early on.

00:01:40.260 --> 00:01:46.320
And when I started to do different activities,
like ballet and wanted to try skating, my

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:50.930
mom asked the pediatrician if it was OK, if
it was an OK activity.

00:01:50.930 --> 00:01:56.590
And I think he thought it was wonderful because
it would just help with the coordination and

00:01:56.590 --> 00:01:57.590
everything.

00:01:57.590 --> 00:02:03.620
And I'm lucky that my parents took the initiative
and had the corrections done early on.

00:02:03.620 --> 00:02:05.810
And it didn't seem to affect my skating.

00:02:05.810 --> 00:02:06.810
[laughs]

00:02:06.810 --> 00:02:09.950
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Was it your choice to
begin skating, or was that something your

00:02:09.950 --> 00:02:11.519
parents came up with?

00:02:11.519 --> 00:02:13.310
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: It was definitely my choice.

00:02:13.310 --> 00:02:14.310
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: OK.

00:02:14.310 --> 00:02:19.909
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: I had seen a local ice
show and remembered Dorothy Hamill had just

00:02:19.909 --> 00:02:24.280
won the Olympics a few years earlier, so she
was my childhood idol.

00:02:24.280 --> 00:02:27.120
And I just wanted to try skating as well.

00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:33.040
So, my older sister, Lori, actually started
skating for a couple of months, but she didn't

00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:34.189
really like it.

00:02:34.189 --> 00:02:39.029
But being my older sister, I still wanted
to try it and just loved it the very first

00:02:39.029 --> 00:02:40.029
time.

00:02:40.029 --> 00:02:41.029
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: OK.

00:02:41.029 --> 00:02:49.029
And did you, at what point did this drive
to actually keep competing and to pursue going

00:02:49.029 --> 00:02:52.760
to Regionals and Nationals and Sectionals
and all of that, when did that kick in?

00:02:52.760 --> 00:02:54.910
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Well, everything just
snowballed.

00:02:54.910 --> 00:02:58.639
I mean, you start out once a week going to
group classes.

00:02:58.639 --> 00:03:00.659
And I was having fun.

00:03:00.659 --> 00:03:06.109
And then, I think maybe a year or so after
I started skating, taking part in my first

00:03:06.109 --> 00:03:15.480
competition that was just rink-wide and coming
11th out of 12th, wasn't what I was hoping

00:03:15.480 --> 00:03:16.480
for.

00:03:16.480 --> 00:03:17.480
[laughs]

00:03:17.480 --> 00:03:20.310
So, I think that stoked the fire . Like, "Well,
how come I didn't get a medal?"

00:03:20.310 --> 00:03:24.769
And my mom's like, "Well, you have to be in
the top three to get a medal."

00:03:24.769 --> 00:03:27.079
So, I think at that point I was like, "I want
a medal.

00:03:27.079 --> 00:03:30.129
[giggles] [audience laughs]Every time I go
out there I wanna win a medal."

00:03:30.129 --> 00:03:37.309
And I think that resonated with me and it's
like, "OK, I need to improve."

00:03:37.309 --> 00:03:42.480
And when I'm competing, you have other competitors
that you're being compared to or whatever.

00:03:42.480 --> 00:03:43.480
So, I don't know.

00:03:43.480 --> 00:03:49.930
I think I just loved the skating so much and
competition, which was part of it.

00:03:49.930 --> 00:03:55.780
And pretty soon, you're competing in your
Northern California area.

00:03:55.780 --> 00:03:57.939
And then I was competing for the West Coast.

00:03:57.939 --> 00:04:02.370
So, it just grew from liking the ice shows.

00:04:02.370 --> 00:04:03.370
[giggles]

00:04:03.370 --> 00:04:04.629
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: You actually started--.

00:04:04.629 --> 00:04:06.150
Did you start off as a single skater?

00:04:06.150 --> 00:04:11.480
You were actually competing pretty, on the
National level, as a pair skater as well.

00:04:11.480 --> 00:04:13.480
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: I did compete in both.

00:04:13.480 --> 00:04:19.540
I started skating when I was six, so I skated
individual until I was eleven years old.

00:04:19.540 --> 00:04:22.830
And then that's when I met my partner, Rudy
Galindo.

00:04:22.830 --> 00:04:24.730
He was 13 at the time.

00:04:24.730 --> 00:04:28.880
He had just won the Novice National Championships
in singles.

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:32.460
And I think people were going, "Oh, you're
both so tiny and cute.

00:04:32.460 --> 00:04:34.090
You should skate pairs together."

00:04:34.090 --> 00:04:35.090
[laughter]

00:04:35.090 --> 00:04:36.330
So I said, "OK.

00:04:36.330 --> 00:04:37.900
It sounds like fun."

00:04:37.900 --> 00:04:40.650
So, we did it for fun, really.

00:04:40.650 --> 00:04:47.500
And our pair coach just taught us what he
could and we went to competitions.

00:04:47.500 --> 00:04:55.560
And before we knew it, we were at National
Championships in Novice Pairs.

00:04:55.560 --> 00:05:01.340
And then we won Junior Pairs, maybe I think
four years into our partnership together.

00:05:01.340 --> 00:05:04.700
So, we were having some great success.

00:05:04.700 --> 00:05:10.310
And I think because we were both strong single
skaters and coming together, but we had fun.

00:05:10.310 --> 00:05:14.390
We went as far as two-time US Pair Champions.

00:05:14.390 --> 00:05:16.390
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: At the senior level.

00:05:16.390 --> 00:05:17.570
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: At the senior level.

00:05:17.570 --> 00:05:23.340
Went to World's and we were fifth at the World
Championships two years in a row.

00:05:23.340 --> 00:05:28.970
And so, I think success came early and fast
for us as a pair team.

00:05:28.970 --> 00:05:34.420
And then at the same time, I continued on
with my singles career.

00:05:34.420 --> 00:05:39.670
So, keeping, developing there as well.

00:05:39.670 --> 00:05:45.650
But I think at the time, we were competing
against, in the pairs category, the top Russian,

00:05:45.650 --> 00:05:48.560
the top Czechoslovakian and Canadian teams.

00:05:48.560 --> 00:05:54.080
So, for us to be fifth two years in a row
was really I think as far as we thought we

00:05:54.080 --> 00:05:55.080
could go.

00:05:55.080 --> 00:06:00.120
And it was time to make a decision either
way 'cause juggling both disciplines was getting

00:06:00.120 --> 00:06:02.650
more difficult at that World level.

00:06:02.650 --> 00:06:08.050
And it was a tough decision, but I knew I
would always go back to, or continue on with

00:06:08.050 --> 00:06:09.050
the singles skating.

00:06:09.050 --> 00:06:10.430
So, that's where I turned my focus.

00:06:10.430 --> 00:06:15.440
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: During that time when
you had to make that decision, did you ever,

00:06:15.440 --> 00:06:16.590
what was that process like?

00:06:16.590 --> 00:06:18.590
And did you ever second guess that?

00:06:18.590 --> 00:06:23.240
Or, I mean, I think now looking back, you
guys have both individually and as pairs partners,

00:06:23.240 --> 00:06:24.240
achieved so much.

00:06:24.240 --> 00:06:29.090
I mean, Rudy went on to win the National title
as well.

00:06:29.090 --> 00:06:31.710
But looking forward, you couldn't have known
that.

00:06:31.710 --> 00:06:33.730
And so, what was that like for you?

00:06:33.730 --> 00:06:38.500
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: It was tough because we
had grown up together, literally, from eleven

00:06:38.500 --> 00:06:41.380
to 17, 18 years old.

00:06:41.380 --> 00:06:43.350
And so, making that decision--.

00:06:43.350 --> 00:06:48.340
We had just imagined careers the rest of our
lives together.

00:06:48.340 --> 00:06:51.930
But things change and your goals change.

00:06:51.930 --> 00:06:56.010
So, it was just time to make a decision.

00:06:56.010 --> 00:07:05.190
So, it was tough for a few months and I made
the decision and tried to be as positive as

00:07:05.190 --> 00:07:06.190
I could.

00:07:06.190 --> 00:07:09.500
And I don't think it was as easy on Rudy.

00:07:09.500 --> 00:07:17.180
I think he was hoping that we would continue
on, but I was determined to continue to skate

00:07:17.180 --> 00:07:22.990
and had, like you said, had some great success
as well, winning Nationals and then becoming

00:07:22.990 --> 00:07:25.480
bronze medalist in the world.

00:07:25.480 --> 00:07:30.730
So, I think looking back it was a good decision
for both of us.

00:07:30.730 --> 00:07:31.730
[giggles]

00:07:31.730 --> 00:07:32.730
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Yeah.

00:07:32.730 --> 00:07:33.730
I think so.

00:07:33.730 --> 00:07:34.890
What were the Olympics like for you?

00:07:34.890 --> 00:07:35.920
What was that?

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:38.170
Can you tell us a little bit about that experience?

00:07:38.170 --> 00:07:40.840
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Absolutely.

00:07:40.840 --> 00:07:44.060
Olympic year was just a whirlwind.

00:07:44.060 --> 00:07:47.260
And I think my goal was just to make the Olympic
team.

00:07:47.260 --> 00:07:53.770
The year before, I had won World's and it
wasn't really until a year before the Olympics

00:07:53.770 --> 00:07:54.770
where I thought, "Wow.

00:07:54.770 --> 00:07:57.020
I actually have a shot at making the Olympic
team.

00:07:57.020 --> 00:08:01.350
Now I can let myself believe that I can actually
be there."

00:08:01.350 --> 00:08:05.690
So, at the US National Championships, I went
in.

00:08:05.690 --> 00:08:09.420
I had never won a national title ever in singles.

00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:13.389
I had already won two pair titles--actually,
three 'cause we won juniors--but I had never

00:08:13.389 --> 00:08:14.389
won singles.

00:08:14.389 --> 00:08:17.530
I was always second in every level coming
up.

00:08:17.530 --> 00:08:21.150
So, I actually won my first national title.

00:08:21.150 --> 00:08:26.530
And so, that just gave me a lot of confidence
going into the Olympics the next month.

00:08:26.530 --> 00:08:30.190
And I was just so honored to be named to the
team.

00:08:30.190 --> 00:08:33.090
I think once I was there, it was like, "Well,
I'm here now.

00:08:33.090 --> 00:08:34.290
Whatever happens happens.

00:08:34.290 --> 00:08:39.430
[presenter giggles] Of course, I want to skate
my best and skate well because I've trained

00:08:39.430 --> 00:08:40.599
so hard to get here."

00:08:40.599 --> 00:08:45.210
But the gold medal was something I didn't
wanna think about.

00:08:45.210 --> 00:08:46.210
I don't know.

00:08:46.210 --> 00:08:47.570
I didn't wanna jinx myself.

00:08:47.570 --> 00:08:51.760
But I knew if I skated as well as I could,
I would have a good shot at it.

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:56.490
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: So, I was actually listening
to a talk recently by an author named Joshua

00:08:56.490 --> 00:09:00.630
Foer and he wrote a book called "Moonwalking
with Einstein."

00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:03.860
And so in this talk he was talking about just
the importance of stepping outside of your

00:09:03.860 --> 00:09:04.860
comfort zone.

00:09:04.860 --> 00:09:07.070
He actually used figure skating as an example.

00:09:07.070 --> 00:09:12.640
So, what he said was the best figure skaters
actually spend more time falling than they

00:09:12.640 --> 00:09:16.270
do practicing the jumps that they know that
they can land.

00:09:16.270 --> 00:09:18.620
Did you find that to be your case in your
situation?

00:09:18.620 --> 00:09:21.230
'Cause I know when I was skating,

00:09:21.230 --> 00:09:24.310
I'm like, "OK, let's stick to my axel.

00:09:24.310 --> 00:09:29.330
Coast on my axel for a while before moving
on to my double "sal"."

00:09:29.330 --> 00:09:36.760
And it's probably why I didn't go to the Olympics,
[giggles] but did you find that to be the

00:09:36.760 --> 00:09:37.760
case?

00:09:37.760 --> 00:09:38.760
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Yeah, definitely.

00:09:38.760 --> 00:09:43.710
I think coming up as a skater, you know in
order to get to the next level or learn that

00:09:43.710 --> 00:09:47.350
next jump or spin or whatever, you're gonna
make a lot of mistakes.

00:09:47.350 --> 00:09:48.790
So, definitely.

00:09:48.790 --> 00:09:54.330
I remember working on by double axel, which
is a big step--.

00:09:54.330 --> 00:09:57.640
It's the hardest double to learn.

00:09:57.640 --> 00:10:02.640
And just saying, "OK, I'm gonna work 20 minutes
on my double axel."

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:06.880
And it would just be literally skate around,
jump, fall, skate around, jump, fall, skate

00:10:06.880 --> 00:10:07.880
around--.

00:10:07.880 --> 00:10:08.880
[giggles]

00:10:08.880 --> 00:10:09.880
For 20 minutes.

00:10:09.880 --> 00:10:13.839
And you're just waiting for that moment for
it to click.

00:10:13.839 --> 00:10:21.260
And I think my coaches at the time were just
very good at instilling in me, "OK, you just,

00:10:21.260 --> 00:10:22.980
this is just what you have to do."

00:10:22.980 --> 00:10:27.830
[chuckles] And because you look around and
you see other people doing it and are landing

00:10:27.830 --> 00:10:32.460
the jump that it motivates you to keep doing
it and finally get it.

00:10:32.460 --> 00:10:37.500
So, I think ultimately, finally, she offered
like a hundred dollars [laughter] if I could

00:10:37.500 --> 00:10:38.500
land it clean.

00:10:38.500 --> 00:10:42.490
And that ramped up the practice a little more.

00:10:42.490 --> 00:10:44.870
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: And then how long did
it take you for it to click after that?

00:10:44.870 --> 00:10:45.870
[laughing]

00:10:45.870 --> 00:10:47.440
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Like a week.

00:10:47.440 --> 00:10:48.440
[giggles]

00:10:48.440 --> 00:10:49.440
[laughter]

00:10:49.440 --> 00:10:50.440
So, yeah.

00:10:50.440 --> 00:10:51.680
I mean, in skating, it's all about falling.

00:10:51.680 --> 00:10:56.839
And the first thing we learn as skaters stepping
onto the ice is how to get up when you fall

00:10:56.839 --> 00:10:58.540
because it's gonna happen.

00:10:58.540 --> 00:10:59.540
[giggles]

00:10:59.540 --> 00:11:00.540
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Yeah.

00:11:00.540 --> 00:11:05.930
So, I thought we'd switch gears a little bit
and talk about your book.

00:11:05.930 --> 00:11:09.150
What led you to wanting to write a book?

00:11:09.150 --> 00:11:10.740
And how did you come up with this idea?

00:11:10.740 --> 00:11:13.080
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: I think--.

00:11:13.080 --> 00:11:16.870
I worked with children quite a bit.

00:11:16.870 --> 00:11:23.880
I've had a foundation for 15 years that has
centered on the needs of children for us,

00:11:23.880 --> 00:11:28.360
so I've always wanted to do a children's book.

00:11:28.360 --> 00:11:33.770
But it was never, I guess, in the forefront
of my priorities.

00:11:33.770 --> 00:11:39.000
But I think, my own two children, becoming
a mother, really inspired me.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:43.930
When I started working on the book, they were
four and six, so perfectly in that age range

00:11:43.930 --> 00:11:44.970
that I wanted to target.

00:11:44.970 --> 00:11:49.980
And I thought it would be just something special
for them to have that Mom wrote a book for

00:11:49.980 --> 00:11:50.980
them.

00:11:50.980 --> 00:11:54.300
[audience laughs lightly]
So, I didn't know where to start, but luckily

00:11:54.300 --> 00:12:02.110
I had a book agent who approached me and said
that she would help me and got involved in

00:12:02.110 --> 00:12:03.750
the process right away.

00:12:03.750 --> 00:12:10.589
And luckily found a publisher in Sourcebooks
that came along and said, "OK, we like your

00:12:10.589 --> 00:12:11.589
story.

00:12:11.589 --> 00:12:13.310
Let's move with it."

00:12:13.310 --> 00:12:18.460
So it was really a labor of love and I didn't
know what would happen with it.

00:12:18.460 --> 00:12:26.180
Of course, always hoping that the story would
grasp and take root and resonate with the

00:12:26.180 --> 00:12:29.100
audience.

00:12:29.100 --> 00:12:33.940
And I guess the concept for the book came
as, well, if I'm gonna do this, looking at

00:12:33.940 --> 00:12:38.600
some of my favorite books or children's books,
they all have some type of message.

00:12:38.600 --> 00:12:43.800
And I wanted a positive message to leave with
the kids and something, possibly, that I had

00:12:43.800 --> 00:12:47.950
learned through skating to pass on to them.

00:12:47.950 --> 00:12:51.600
So, that's where the concept of the book came
about from.

00:12:51.600 --> 00:12:53.180
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: OK.

00:12:53.180 --> 00:12:57.380
So, we have, actually, a couple kids in the
audience here.

00:12:57.380 --> 00:13:01.050
I believe some Googlers brought their kids.

00:13:01.050 --> 00:13:04.410
[giggles] Did you wanna do a little bit of
book reading for us?

00:13:04.410 --> 00:13:05.410
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Yes.

00:13:05.410 --> 00:13:06.410
Sure.

00:13:06.410 --> 00:13:07.410
Definitely.

00:13:07.410 --> 00:13:08.410
All right.

00:13:08.410 --> 00:13:12.550
So, it's called "Dream Big, Little Pig," and
illustrated by Tim Bowers.

00:13:12.550 --> 00:13:16.050
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: All right.

00:13:16.050 --> 00:13:17.790
[children talking]

00:13:17.790 --> 00:13:22.170
[Kristi Yamaguchi reads from book]

00:13:22.170 --> 00:13:26.520
"Poppy was a pig--a pot-bellied, waddling,
toddling pig.

00:13:26.520 --> 00:13:32.300
She was a pig with dreams and she was a pig
who dreamed big.

00:13:32.300 --> 00:13:37.810
She wanted to be a star.

00:13:37.810 --> 00:13:42.630
Poppy had always dreamed of being a posh prima
ballerina.

00:13:42.630 --> 00:13:48.890
“She tried out for Swan Lake, a famous ballet,
but Poppy was not graceful.

00:13:48.890 --> 00:13:53.830
In fact, she was quite clumsy.

00:13:53.830 --> 00:14:00.770
'Follow your dreams!' said Poppy's mother,
who loved her no matter what.

00:14:00.770 --> 00:14:06.060
'You go, Girl!' said Poppy's grandparents,
who were her biggest fans.

00:14:06.060 --> 00:14:12.149
'Dream big, Pig!' said Poppy's best friend
Emma, who was always there for her.

00:14:12.149 --> 00:14:16.649
'Dancing is just not for you,' said the people
in charge of the ballet.

00:14:16.649 --> 00:14:19.750
“'Try something else.'

00:14:19.750 --> 00:14:28.149
So, Poppy tried out for Singing Stars, a popular
chorus competition.

00:14:28.149 --> 00:14:32.149
She'd always dreamed of being a soulful singer.

00:14:32.149 --> 00:14:34.890
But Poppy sang off-key.

00:14:34.890 --> 00:14:37.060
And to be honest, she couldn't really carry
a tune."

00:14:37.060 --> 00:14:39.840
&gt;&gt;Child: Look at Poppy!

00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:40.840
[laughter]

00:14:40.840 --> 00:14:43.820
"'Follow your dreams!' said Poppy's mother.

00:14:43.820 --> 00:14:46.400
‘You go, Girl!' said Poppy's grandparents.

00:14:46.400 --> 00:14:49.450
‘Dream big, Pig!' said Emma.

00:14:49.450 --> 00:14:54.160
‘Singing is just not for you,' said the
people in charge of the competition.

00:14:54.160 --> 00:14:57.830
‘Try something else.'

00:14:57.830 --> 00:15:03.670
“So, Poppy tried out for Supermodel Search.

00:15:03.670 --> 00:15:10.310
[audience chuckles] She had always dreamed
of being a big time, splashy supermodel.

00:15:10.310 --> 00:15:14.110
But Poppy was not very glitzy or glittery.

00:15:14.110 --> 00:15:17.800
And she even tripped on her fancy gown.

00:15:17.800 --> 00:15:23.640
'Follow your dreams!' said Poppy's mother.

00:15:23.640 --> 00:15:26.570
'You go, Girl!' said Poppy's grandparents.

00:15:26.570 --> 00:15:30.050
“'Dream big, Pig!' said Emma.

00:15:30.050 --> 00:15:34.490
'Modeling is just not for you,' said the people
in charge of the search.

00:15:34.490 --> 00:15:37.920
'Try something else.'

00:15:37.920 --> 00:15:42.740
But Poppy didn't know what else to try.

00:15:42.740 --> 00:15:48.910
And as she wandered through New Pork City,
she began to wonder if her dreams would really

00:15:48.910 --> 00:15:51.950
come true.

00:15:51.950 --> 00:15:59.630
“Poppy was about to give up when she heard
her mother say, 'Just follow your heart.

00:15:59.630 --> 00:16:02.769
Remember, we love you no matter what.'

00:16:02.769 --> 00:16:06.950
And her grandparents cheer, 'We're your biggest
fans!'

00:16:06.950 --> 00:16:10.600
And her best friend Emma's squeal, 'We're
here for you!'

00:16:10.600 --> 00:16:11.980
Poppy smiled.

00:16:11.980 --> 00:16:15.180
“She knew just what to do.

00:16:15.180 --> 00:16:20.200
When Poppy thought about all the things she
truly loved, her friends and family were at

00:16:20.200 --> 00:16:21.720
the top of her list.

00:16:21.720 --> 00:16:27.950
So the next day, Poppy invited Emma for a
Pig's Day Out in the park.

00:16:27.950 --> 00:16:34.350
While giggling and strolling along, they spotted
an ice rink.

00:16:34.350 --> 00:16:39.830
Poppy and Emma watched the skaters skimming
and spinning, swooping and swizzling on the

00:16:39.830 --> 00:16:40.830
ice.

00:16:40.830 --> 00:16:45.790
“Poppy realized that it was the most beautiful
sight that she had ever seen.

00:16:45.790 --> 00:16:47.810
Her heart danced with joy.

00:16:47.810 --> 00:16:53.550
Emma saw a twinkle in Poppy's eye and high-fived
her friend.

00:16:53.550 --> 00:16:56.670
'Dream big, Pig!' she cheered.

00:16:56.670 --> 00:17:02.690
So Poppy waddled and toddled right up to the
skating teacher and said, 'I'd like to be

00:17:02.690 --> 00:17:05.220
a spectacular ice skating star.'

00:17:05.220 --> 00:17:13.120
“'A pig on ice,' the teacher pondered.

00:17:13.120 --> 00:17:17.179
'Honey, I don't know if that's possible.'

00:17:17.179 --> 00:17:19.450
'Anything's possible,' said Poppy.

00:17:19.450 --> 00:17:22.150
'I believe in dreaming big.'

00:17:22.150 --> 00:17:23.569
The teacher shrugged.

00:17:23.569 --> 00:17:25.730
'As you wish,' she said.

00:17:25.730 --> 00:17:30.460
'We'll see if the pig's got pizazz.'

00:17:30.460 --> 00:17:32.010
Poppy laced up her skates.

00:17:32.010 --> 00:17:35.360
She slipped and slid all over the ice.

00:17:35.360 --> 00:17:37.650
“And she fell.

00:17:37.650 --> 00:17:45.360
But this time, Poppy got up over and over
and over.

00:17:45.360 --> 00:17:49.080
She shuffled and stumbled and fumbled and
fell.

00:17:49.080 --> 00:17:55.960
But by the time the rink closed for the night,
Poppy was skating more than she was falling.

00:17:55.960 --> 00:18:01.320
And it felt like magic.

00:18:01.320 --> 00:18:03.820
Poppy returned to the rink the very next day.

00:18:03.820 --> 00:18:08.630
“Her cheeks were pink with winter wind and
excitement.

00:18:08.630 --> 00:18:13.170
She was so happy gliding, sliding, and tumbling
and bumbling on the ice.

00:18:13.170 --> 00:18:16.910
She didn't even notice that she wasn't perfect.

00:18:16.910 --> 00:18:19.580
And nobody else did, either.

00:18:19.580 --> 00:18:26.820
Now a most persistent pig, Poppy learned to
twirl and swirl and do dips and lunges and

00:18:26.820 --> 00:18:27.820
splits.

00:18:27.820 --> 00:18:31.900
Poppy learned to do jumps and spirals and
lifts.

00:18:31.900 --> 00:18:40.360
“Before she knew it, more and more skaters
stopped to watch Poppy practice.

00:18:40.360 --> 00:18:41.890
She was quite a sight.

00:18:41.890 --> 00:18:46.580
She even had her picture on the front page
of the newspaper.

00:18:46.580 --> 00:18:48.360
Poppy felt like a star.

00:18:48.360 --> 00:18:53.390
Some of her fans made t-shirts that read,
'Follow your dreams.'

00:18:53.390 --> 00:18:56.860
Other wore hats that said, 'Dream big, Pig!'

00:18:56.860 --> 00:19:00.460
And tote bags declared, 'You go, Girl!'

00:19:00.460 --> 00:19:02.929
Poppy's dreams had come true.

00:19:02.929 --> 00:19:08.740
“Time went by, but Poppy didn't stop dreaming.

00:19:08.740 --> 00:19:12.410
One day, she decided to be a pilot.

00:19:12.410 --> 00:19:16.560
She wanted to parachute and be the first sky-diving
pig.

00:19:16.560 --> 00:19:19.870
'When pigs fly,' said the other pilots.

00:19:19.870 --> 00:19:22.620
But they did not know Poppy.

00:19:22.620 --> 00:19:25.330
She was a pig who dreamed big.

00:19:25.330 --> 00:19:27.520
The end."

00:19:27.520 --> 00:19:28.620
[applause]

00:19:28.620 --> 00:19:30.809
Thank you.

00:19:30.809 --> 00:19:33.000
Thank you.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:34.100
Thanks.

00:19:34.100 --> 00:19:41.570
So, this is a fun little story about a little
pig who kept trying and finally found her

00:19:41.570 --> 00:19:42.570
passion.

00:19:42.570 --> 00:19:47.270
So, I thought it was a good thing for kids
and adults to keep dreaming.

00:19:47.270 --> 00:19:51.280
You can never dream too big.

00:19:51.280 --> 00:19:54.760
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Have your daughters actually
started skating?

00:19:54.760 --> 00:20:00.360
I know between you and your husband, you're
both spectacular on the ice.

00:20:00.360 --> 00:20:02.020
Have they taken to skating at all?

00:20:02.020 --> 00:20:05.560
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: They like to go out and
skate with their friends.

00:20:05.560 --> 00:20:10.910
We'll get on the ice with them every now and
then, but they run away from us because they

00:20:10.910 --> 00:20:14.230
don't like Mommy telling them what to do.

00:20:14.230 --> 00:20:15.360
[laughter]

00:20:15.360 --> 00:20:18.179
So it's almost better they take lessons from
someone else.

00:20:18.179 --> 00:20:20.100
And they're just beginning.

00:20:20.100 --> 00:20:21.100
They're in group classes.

00:20:21.100 --> 00:20:25.929
So as long as they can skate and move around
on the ice, that's all we care about.

00:20:25.929 --> 00:20:29.390
We don't expect them to do shows or compete
or anything.

00:20:29.390 --> 00:20:34.110
But you have to know how to skate in our family.

00:20:34.110 --> 00:20:35.110
[laughter]

00:20:35.110 --> 00:20:39.180
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: And have you, do you still
skate pretty regularly?

00:20:39.180 --> 00:20:43.540
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Well, unfortunately, I
haven't really been skating much lately.

00:20:43.540 --> 00:20:46.890
I think my last performance was almost two
years ago.

00:20:46.890 --> 00:20:54.100
So, it's, my priority now is my family and
keeping up with the girl's schedules.

00:20:54.100 --> 00:20:56.720
But we're still involved with skating a little
bit.

00:20:56.720 --> 00:21:03.100
I'm part of the US Figure Skating Mentoring
program, where some of their past skaters

00:21:03.100 --> 00:21:05.210
are mentoring the younger skaters coming up.

00:21:05.210 --> 00:21:12.140
And then also, hosting a couple of the television
shows that are broadcast on NBC.

00:21:12.140 --> 00:21:15.200
So, a little bit here and there.

00:21:15.200 --> 00:21:18.010
But I miss it on the ice a little bit.

00:21:18.010 --> 00:21:19.669
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Yeah.

00:21:19.669 --> 00:21:24.530
And I mean, just listening to you read the
book, I mean it sounds like Poppy went through

00:21:24.530 --> 00:21:28.260
a couple different things before stumbling
across skating.

00:21:28.260 --> 00:21:32.300
And how important do you think is raw talent?

00:21:32.300 --> 00:21:39.340
I guess just sheer determination in pursuing
something that you're interested in and ultimately

00:21:39.340 --> 00:21:40.340
succeeding at?

00:21:40.340 --> 00:21:43.570
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: I think it's--.

00:21:43.570 --> 00:21:47.780
My grandmother always said, "You have to have
the three D's.

00:21:47.780 --> 00:21:51.740
Determination, Dedication, and Desire."

00:21:51.740 --> 00:21:55.100
And if you don't have those, then you're not
gonna have success.

00:21:55.100 --> 00:22:00.660
And I completely believe that because I was
not the most talented.

00:22:00.660 --> 00:22:03.550
My mom would always say, "Well, they're learning
it much faster than you.

00:22:03.550 --> 00:22:04.550
And why can't you do that?

00:22:04.550 --> 00:22:06.010
[laughs] They're already doing that."

00:22:06.010 --> 00:22:07.070
And she knew.

00:22:07.070 --> 00:22:12.710
She's like, "Well, I think you just need to
work a little harder in order to progress

00:22:12.710 --> 00:22:14.590
like the other kids."

00:22:14.590 --> 00:22:15.660
And I think that was good.

00:22:15.660 --> 00:22:22.770
It taught me a work ethic and I wasn't afraid
to work and was willing to in order to learn

00:22:22.770 --> 00:22:23.960
something new.

00:22:23.960 --> 00:22:32.280
So, I've seen a lot of talented skaters come
up really quickly and when it got tough, they

00:22:32.280 --> 00:22:33.280
seemed to fizzle out.

00:22:33.280 --> 00:22:39.220
And I think you have to be willing to put
in that extra amount of work--stay on the

00:22:39.220 --> 00:22:44.520
ice an extra few minutes in order to separate
yourself from the rest.

00:22:44.520 --> 00:22:46.809
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Yeah.

00:22:46.809 --> 00:22:49.310
And I think we do have a lot of parents in
the audience right now.

00:22:49.310 --> 00:22:57.370
Do you have any advice for the parents here
as to how to encourage their children to be

00:22:57.370 --> 00:22:58.370
physically active?

00:22:58.370 --> 00:23:03.179
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Well, like all parents,
I'm still learning along the way, too.

00:23:03.179 --> 00:23:06.290
Mine are just five and seven now.

00:23:06.290 --> 00:23:11.590
But I think both my husband and I were so
involved with sports our entire lives and

00:23:11.590 --> 00:23:15.550
knowing that being involved in sports taught
us a lot of things.

00:23:15.550 --> 00:23:18.030
I think it gave us a lot of confidence.

00:23:18.030 --> 00:23:23.460
It taught us how to respect ourselves, our
competitors, our own bodies.

00:23:23.460 --> 00:23:28.570
So, I think those are all important things
that kids can learn through sports.

00:23:28.570 --> 00:23:34.950
And something that we're trying to encourage
our own children to get involved in because

00:23:34.950 --> 00:23:38.360
teamwork and being part of that.

00:23:38.360 --> 00:23:45.559
And there's so many great lessons to be learned
that I think to encourage them, it's hard

00:23:45.559 --> 00:23:46.559
to keep pushing.

00:23:46.559 --> 00:23:52.539
But I think trying to help them find maybe
what their passion is and then supporting

00:23:52.539 --> 00:23:55.210
it once they do find it.

00:23:55.210 --> 00:23:57.220
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: And you also--.

00:23:57.220 --> 00:24:02.169
Going along this theme of dreams, you also
run the Always Dream Foundation.

00:24:02.169 --> 00:24:04.460
And you've been involved with this for, was
it 15 years?

00:24:04.460 --> 00:24:05.460
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Yeah.

00:24:05.460 --> 00:24:06.460
Actually, almost 16 now, yeah.

00:24:06.460 --> 00:24:07.760
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Sixteen years.

00:24:07.760 --> 00:24:12.010
So, can you tell us a little bit about that
and the work that you do through your foundation?

00:24:12.010 --> 00:24:13.240
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Sure.

00:24:13.240 --> 00:24:14.410
It's Always Dream.

00:24:14.410 --> 00:24:20.550
We've, or I, established it because I was
inspired by the Make A Wish Foundation, which

00:24:20.550 --> 00:24:23.840
does a lot of work with children and their
families.

00:24:23.840 --> 00:24:31.120
So, I decided to create something that will
help touch the lives of children out there

00:24:31.120 --> 00:24:33.919
and in all genres.

00:24:33.919 --> 00:24:40.140
We've helped children with disabilities, to
disadvantaged children, under-served children,

00:24:40.140 --> 00:24:47.150
children of tragedies like Hurricane Katrina
and the recent tsunami in Japan.

00:24:47.150 --> 00:24:53.620
So, we've dedicated ourselves to embrace the
hopes and dreams of children in whatever way

00:24:53.620 --> 00:24:55.110
we can.

00:24:55.110 --> 00:25:01.870
Now we are turning our focus more on education,
again, inspired by my children entering public

00:25:01.870 --> 00:25:03.220
school.

00:25:03.220 --> 00:25:12.370
So, we really wanna try to help the literacy
component and really target early childhood

00:25:12.370 --> 00:25:20.220
literacy and technology and finding a way
to combine those two and make a difference,

00:25:20.220 --> 00:25:25.559
because we know that reading levels--and especially
at the 3rd Grade level--will help determine

00:25:25.559 --> 00:25:28.590
your success in not only school, but in life
as well.

00:25:28.590 --> 00:25:33.840
So, if we can make a difference there, especially
in the under-served areas where these children

00:25:33.840 --> 00:25:41.470
don't have access to books, and we want to
teach them to learn to love reading and to

00:25:41.470 --> 00:25:43.860
love books as early on as possible.

00:25:43.860 --> 00:25:45.630
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: OK.

