00:29:54.240 --> 00:29:55.240
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Oh, all right.

00:29:55.240 --> 00:30:01.000
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #3: I just wanted to ask, after you
achieved your amazing success at the Olympics

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:04.490
and such, did you ever have moments after
that saying, "How can I top this?

00:30:04.490 --> 00:30:05.490
What do I do next?

00:30:05.490 --> 00:30:06.600
Where do I go from here?"

00:30:06.600 --> 00:30:08.640
Did you ever feel lost at all?

00:30:08.640 --> 00:30:11.809
Or, you hadn't actually thought past that
point or anything like that?

00:30:11.809 --> 00:30:13.620
And how did you come to where you are now?

00:30:13.620 --> 00:30:19.570
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: I probably have thoughts
like that more now than I did after the Olympics.

00:30:19.570 --> 00:30:27.260
I think I was really fortunate that in skating,
I was able to look beyond the Olympics and

00:30:27.260 --> 00:30:31.679
see a career path ahead.

00:30:31.679 --> 00:30:40.850
Back in 1992, there was a very rich professional
skating atmosphere to join, so I knew if I

00:30:40.850 --> 00:30:42.280
didn't continue to compete,

00:30:42.280 --> 00:30:44.710
I wanted to tour as a professional.

00:30:44.710 --> 00:30:47.500
And that was really my ultimate dream.

00:30:47.500 --> 00:30:49.390
When I was little, it wasn't really the Olympics.

00:30:49.390 --> 00:30:50.390
I didn't know what that was.

00:30:50.390 --> 00:30:53.559
It was to be a professional skater touring
the world.

00:30:53.559 --> 00:30:59.140
So, I knew I wanted to do that for several
years after the Olympics.

00:30:59.140 --> 00:31:02.610
But there were times when like, "Is that like
the highlight of my life?

00:31:02.610 --> 00:31:04.080
How sad at 20 I peaked?

00:31:04.080 --> 00:31:06.029
What does gonna happen now?"

00:31:06.029 --> 00:31:07.029
[laughter]

00:31:07.029 --> 00:31:15.250
But I think using that fear and then finding
other challenges to face kept me going.

00:31:15.250 --> 00:31:22.080
And dedicating myself to a ten-year professional
career was one, and then looking beyond that,

00:31:22.080 --> 00:31:28.850
I knew family was another that the timing
was just right.

00:31:28.850 --> 00:31:34.230
And then, once my kids were older and I felt,
"OK, I have time now to maybe do some other

00:31:34.230 --> 00:31:38.640
things," then that's when Dancing With the
Stars came about and other projects.

00:31:38.640 --> 00:31:39.929
So, I don't know.

00:31:39.929 --> 00:31:46.960
I think I feel the most alive and the most
energy when I have something to look forward

00:31:46.960 --> 00:31:49.080
to and a new challenge in front of me.

00:31:49.080 --> 00:31:50.820
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #3: Thank you.

00:31:50.820 --> 00:31:56.039
&gt;&gt;Male Helper: So Erica, we might need to
take some VC questions .

00:31:56.039 --> 00:31:57.770
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Oh, hello?

00:31:57.770 --> 00:31:59.510
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #4: Hi Kristi.

00:31:59.510 --> 00:32:00.840
Thank you for coming.

00:32:00.840 --> 00:32:02.500
I actually met you.

00:32:02.500 --> 00:32:04.080
This is the second time I'm watching you talk.

00:32:04.080 --> 00:32:07.130
The first time I saw you talk was back in
Iceoplex.

00:32:07.130 --> 00:32:12.440
And this was when I was in 7th Grade.

00:32:12.440 --> 00:32:19.210
You kinda showed up, in Logitech Skating or
something in Fremont off of Warm Springs.

00:32:19.210 --> 00:32:23.179
But I remember being in 7th Grade and seeing
you there and I was just so ecstatic.

00:32:23.179 --> 00:32:25.590
So, I'm glad to see you again.

00:32:25.590 --> 00:32:28.340
I had a quick question for you because I used
to skate.

00:32:28.340 --> 00:32:33.299
I mean, nothing really crazy or anything,
but the highest jump I could do was a double

00:32:33.299 --> 00:32:34.299
loop.

00:32:34.299 --> 00:32:39.409
And so, I haven't skated in a really, really,
really long time and I'm afraid to back because

00:32:39.409 --> 00:32:42.571
I just don't wanna be disappointed to not
be able to do anything except skate around

00:32:42.571 --> 00:32:43.750
in a circle.

00:32:43.750 --> 00:32:48.980
[laughter]
So, I wanted to see how you feel about going

00:32:48.980 --> 00:32:53.640
back to skating 'cause you said you haven't
skated, or your last show was two years ago.

00:32:53.640 --> 00:32:58.880
And also, how do you feel if you can't do
a certain jump that you used to could do like,

00:32:58.880 --> 00:32:59.940
with your eyes closed?

00:32:59.940 --> 00:33:02.799
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: I feel your pain, for
sure.

00:33:02.799 --> 00:33:08.529
[audience chuckles] I think my first experience
with that was taking a break for the birth

00:33:08.529 --> 00:33:09.630
of our first daughter.

00:33:09.630 --> 00:33:15.900
I had never been off the ice for more than
probably three, four weeks or something.

00:33:15.900 --> 00:33:19.179
So, after she was born, I knew I wanted--.

00:33:19.179 --> 00:33:24.220
I had a little bit more skating left in me
and so, it was just getting back on the ice

00:33:24.220 --> 00:33:25.909
and getting back in shape slowly.

00:33:25.909 --> 00:33:30.350
But now, it's been a couple years since I've
really skated skated.

00:33:30.350 --> 00:33:37.659
I mean, my best advice would be to start off
ice training a little bit first.

00:33:37.659 --> 00:33:42.980
I think just preparing the body to get on
the ice, because otherwise you'll just be

00:33:42.980 --> 00:33:44.670
really frustrated I think.

00:33:44.670 --> 00:33:51.470
[giggles] So, I think Pilates and all of that,
yoga, any type of cardio you can do off the

00:33:51.470 --> 00:33:55.960
ice will help your body get prepared to go
on the ice.

00:33:55.960 --> 00:34:02.610
Because once you put the skates on, you wanna
be able to skate around and not--, and have

00:34:02.610 --> 00:34:05.840
the strength to do that and the stamina to
do that.

00:34:05.840 --> 00:34:06.840
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #4: Yeah.

00:34:06.840 --> 00:34:09.250
I remember before, I had no problems like
launching myself into the air and falling.

00:34:09.250 --> 00:34:15.379
It was kinda fun, but now the thought of that
is just scary and I can't do it.

00:34:15.379 --> 00:34:16.379
[giggles]

00:34:16.379 --> 00:34:20.200
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Yeah, I think the older
you get, those pain receptors seem to become

00:34:20.200 --> 00:34:21.200
more sensitive.

00:34:21.200 --> 00:34:23.590
[giggles]So, it's, yeah.

00:34:23.590 --> 00:34:24.599
I tend to--.

00:34:24.599 --> 00:34:25.619
It's hard.

00:34:25.619 --> 00:34:29.119
I know I can't do the jumps that I used to
and that's frustrating.

00:34:29.119 --> 00:34:35.220
And my focus isn't on the training anymore,
so I know and I have to be realistic that

00:34:35.220 --> 00:34:37.190
I'm not doing that anymore.

00:34:37.190 --> 00:34:42.280
But that's a big part of the reason why I'm
not performing anymore because when I knew

00:34:42.280 --> 00:34:47.060
I used to perform at this level, it's hard
to accept that, "OK, I'm down here now."

00:34:47.060 --> 00:34:50.490
And maybe that's not how I wanna be seen anymore.

00:34:50.490 --> 00:34:51.490
[giggles]

00:34:51.490 --> 00:34:54.859
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #4: Thank you.

00:34:54.859 --> 00:34:58.350
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #5: Ask her?

00:34:58.350 --> 00:34:59.350
OK.

00:34:59.350 --> 00:35:00.700
I don't know.

00:35:00.700 --> 00:35:05.119
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: How old are you?

00:35:05.119 --> 00:35:10.270
&gt;&gt;MALE #1: How old are you, Mia?

00:35:10.270 --> 00:35:12.480
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #5: Four.

00:35:12.480 --> 00:35:14.690
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Four.

00:35:14.690 --> 00:35:18.369
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #5: I'm really four.

00:35:18.369 --> 00:35:22.180
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #6: When are you planning on coming
out with another book?

00:35:22.180 --> 00:35:26.970
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Actually, I'm working
on book two right now--the follow-up to this

00:35:26.970 --> 00:35:28.240
book about Poppy.

00:35:28.240 --> 00:35:30.990
So, it'll be the same character.

00:35:30.990 --> 00:35:36.600
And it's more of an international feel to
the book.

00:35:36.600 --> 00:35:40.480
And it will be released early March of 2012.

00:35:40.480 --> 00:35:43.230
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #5: Oh, nice.

00:35:43.230 --> 00:35:44.230
[laughter]

00:35:44.230 --> 00:35:46.670
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Thank you.

00:35:46.670 --> 00:35:51.290
Make sure you tell your Mommy you wanna see
the book, too.

00:35:51.290 --> 00:35:53.230
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #5: Yeah.

00:35:53.230 --> 00:35:54.230
OK.

00:35:54.230 --> 00:36:00.530
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: While the mic goes around,
I wanted to ask you who are some of your favorite

00:36:00.530 --> 00:36:01.530
skaters?

00:36:01.530 --> 00:36:03.980
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #5: Excuse me.

00:36:03.980 --> 00:36:07.450
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: The current competitors.

00:36:07.450 --> 00:36:13.250
I think my favorite skaters right now are,
which I, it would've surprised me ten years

00:36:13.250 --> 00:36:18.540
ago if you asked me this, they're actually
ice dancers--Meryl Davis and Charlie White.

00:36:18.540 --> 00:36:20.780
They're the US National Champions.

00:36:20.780 --> 00:36:25.230
Actually, just recently won the World Championships
last March.

00:36:25.230 --> 00:36:31.990
So, they're just incredible, fresh, and gorgeous
on the ice.

00:36:31.990 --> 00:36:37.290
And I think ice dancing has entered a new
era and I don't know.

00:36:37.290 --> 00:36:38.609
I really like it.

00:36:38.609 --> 00:36:42.180
I think they've done a great job representing
the sport.

00:36:42.180 --> 00:36:47.040
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #7: Yeah, so I'm from Fremont, too.

00:36:47.040 --> 00:36:48.230
[laughter]
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Yeah!

00:36:48.230 --> 00:36:49.420
Wow, there's a lot.

00:36:49.420 --> 00:36:56.320
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #7: And my daughter loves the Dreamland
playground, which I think is designed by you.

00:36:56.320 --> 00:36:57.839
The Dreamland.

00:36:57.839 --> 00:36:58.839
I think it's--.

00:36:58.839 --> 00:37:00.920
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Oh, at Central Park?

00:37:00.920 --> 00:37:02.410
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #7: Yeah, at Central Park.

00:37:02.410 --> 00:37:05.660
I forgot exactly what's the name of it, but
she loves it.

00:37:05.660 --> 00:37:10.800
It's really unique playground from any other
place else.

00:37:10.800 --> 00:37:13.369
So, thank you very much.

00:37:13.369 --> 00:37:14.369
[laughs]

00:37:14.369 --> 00:37:22.910
And what brings you to design such nice a
playground and it is very unique and different

00:37:22.910 --> 00:37:23.910
from other places.

00:37:23.910 --> 00:37:24.910
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: OK, yeah.

00:37:24.910 --> 00:37:26.010
She's talking about--.

00:37:26.010 --> 00:37:32.790
We, my foundation, built an Always Dream Play
Park, which is in Central Park in Fremont

00:37:32.790 --> 00:37:34.480
at Lake Elizabeth.

00:37:34.480 --> 00:37:38.150
And it's one of the few of its kind in the
Bay Area.

00:37:38.150 --> 00:37:42.920
it's all-abilities playground.

00:37:42.920 --> 00:37:45.010
Another labor of love for our foundation.

00:37:45.010 --> 00:37:50.010
It was something four, five years in the making
from concept.

00:37:50.010 --> 00:37:52.550
We were working with a lot of children with
disabilities.

00:37:52.550 --> 00:37:56.720
We actually did a summer camp in Hawaii with
kids with disabilities.

00:37:56.720 --> 00:38:03.750
And after the four days, from the children
to the counselors to our board members, we

00:38:03.750 --> 00:38:11.070
were all just transformed and wanted to do
something that was more permanent and serving

00:38:11.070 --> 00:38:12.140
than the four days.

00:38:12.140 --> 00:38:16.300
So, I had heard about these types of playgrounds
and we researched it.

00:38:16.300 --> 00:38:21.660
We found the right architect, actually based
in Berkeley, and came up with the designs

00:38:21.660 --> 00:38:26.220
and ultimately tried to raise the funding.

00:38:26.220 --> 00:38:28.060
So, Fremont was a great partner.

00:38:28.060 --> 00:38:32.240
They're obviously my home town, so they welcomed
this idea.

00:38:32.240 --> 00:38:38.780
And so, we created this playground where kids
of all abilities can play side by side.

00:38:38.780 --> 00:38:40.440
And it's accessible.

00:38:40.440 --> 00:38:50.990
It's fun, even children with sensory issues
can find quiet spots to find solace in.

00:38:50.990 --> 00:38:55.070
And then we're across the street from the
California School of the Deaf and Blind, so

00:38:55.070 --> 00:38:59.950
a couple of things on the playground cater
to that as well.

00:38:59.950 --> 00:39:00.950
So, yeah.

00:39:00.950 --> 00:39:01.950
I don't know.

00:39:01.950 --> 00:39:07.160
It was I think the biggest capital project
that we had ever taken on, but obviously one

00:39:07.160 --> 00:39:10.900
of the most rewarding as well.

00:39:10.900 --> 00:39:16.860
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Any other questions from
the audience?

00:39:16.860 --> 00:39:22.070
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #8: Thank you for coming.

00:39:22.070 --> 00:39:25.780
Sort of on the theme of dreaming big I guess,
so I've always wanted to write children's

00:39:25.780 --> 00:39:26.780
books as well.

00:39:26.780 --> 00:39:31.240
And I was just curious if you have any advice
for someone who hasn't started or doesn't

00:39:31.240 --> 00:39:32.450
even really know how to start.

00:39:32.450 --> 00:39:33.450
Any thought?

00:39:33.450 --> 00:39:34.770
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Yeah.

00:39:34.770 --> 00:39:39.080
I mean, I think the most important thing is
come up with your concept first.

00:39:39.080 --> 00:39:43.650
Like, what you want to accomplish in the story.

00:39:43.650 --> 00:39:45.790
And that's what I came up with here.

00:39:45.790 --> 00:39:47.020
I said I want someone positive.

00:39:47.020 --> 00:39:49.050
I wanna leave a great message.

00:39:49.050 --> 00:39:56.910
I want kids to know that it takes work and
failure to sometimes accomplish your dreams.

00:39:56.910 --> 00:40:01.080
You don't necessarily have to win, but it's
more about giving it your best.

00:40:01.080 --> 00:40:05.390
So it's finding that concept and putting those
together and then finding the character that

00:40:05.390 --> 00:40:12.980
you want to be the one to express these things.

00:40:12.980 --> 00:40:15.680
And then just writing it.

00:40:15.680 --> 00:40:16.680
I don't know.

00:40:16.680 --> 00:40:17.680
It's just jotting down.

00:40:17.680 --> 00:40:19.100
I mean, I just did it on paper.

00:40:19.100 --> 00:40:20.930
And the second book, too.

00:40:20.930 --> 00:40:26.220
I wrote on paper and I'm scratching out and
throwing them away.

00:40:26.220 --> 00:40:27.990
Just the old-fashioned way.

00:40:27.990 --> 00:40:31.200
And when I finally got a manuscript that I
thought was presentable, then, well with the

00:40:31.200 --> 00:40:35.760
first one turned it in and my book agent shopped
it around.

00:40:35.760 --> 00:40:39.300
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #8: And did you already have a relationship
with the illustrator or did you--?

00:40:39.300 --> 00:40:40.300
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: No.

00:40:40.300 --> 00:40:43.450
That came after the publisher came in.

00:40:43.450 --> 00:40:48.350
They had an idea of what they wanted.

00:40:48.350 --> 00:40:51.440
So, they introduced me to Tim via email.

00:40:51.440 --> 00:40:53.670
I've never met him, actually.

00:40:53.670 --> 00:40:57.839
[giggles] But everything was done through
approvals of sketches he turned in.

00:40:57.839 --> 00:41:02.119
And I was just really lucky that I really
liked what he did.

00:41:02.119 --> 00:41:03.119
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #8: Thank you.

00:41:03.119 --> 00:41:04.119
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: You're welcome.

00:41:04.119 --> 00:41:05.119
Right in front.

00:41:05.119 --> 00:41:16.970
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #9: Can you talk a little bit about
your experience on "Dancing With the Stars?"

00:41:16.970 --> 00:41:18.290
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: The question was about
"Dancing With the Stars."

00:41:18.290 --> 00:41:20.290
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Lots of fun.

00:41:20.290 --> 00:41:22.080
I mean, what can you say?

00:41:22.080 --> 00:41:25.990
[giggles]You watch the show and you can tell
everyone's having a lot of fun on it.

00:41:25.990 --> 00:41:32.261
But I think the surprising thing for me was
that it was not so physically demanding, but

00:41:32.261 --> 00:41:35.310
emotionally, mentally demanding as well.

00:41:35.310 --> 00:41:39.079
I think the first few weeks you're just on
a high and you're like, "OK, I wasn't eliminated

00:41:39.079 --> 00:41:40.079
first.

00:41:40.079 --> 00:41:41.079
This is great."

00:41:41.079 --> 00:41:42.079
[laughter]

00:41:42.079 --> 00:41:43.160
"I'm still on the show."

00:41:43.160 --> 00:41:48.050
And then it slowly becomes harder and harder
and there's more pressure and they're expecting

00:41:48.050 --> 00:41:49.410
more of you.

00:41:49.410 --> 00:41:51.150
But it was so much fun.

00:41:51.150 --> 00:41:52.450
I had a great partner.

00:41:52.450 --> 00:41:55.420
Mark Ballas was my professional partner.

00:41:55.420 --> 00:42:02.530
Just talented beyond not only a dancer, but
his first passion is music.

00:42:02.530 --> 00:42:07.790
So, he writes and composes and performs his
own music as well.

00:42:07.790 --> 00:42:10.480
So, just a great group of people.

00:42:10.480 --> 00:42:16.340
It kind of parallels the skating world a little
bit--the dance world--as far as the performing

00:42:16.340 --> 00:42:18.900
side and the characters within it.

00:42:18.900 --> 00:42:19.900
[giggles]

00:42:19.900 --> 00:42:22.020
But it's a great show.

00:42:22.020 --> 00:42:25.450
I think they know what they're doing, obviously.

00:42:25.450 --> 00:42:27.720
The success of it is so big.

00:42:27.720 --> 00:42:37.040
But it was an honor to actually be asked to
be on the show.

00:42:37.040 --> 00:42:38.430
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #9: Just a follow up.

00:42:38.430 --> 00:42:44.020
So, in tying in with your talk about dreaming
big, did you go into that competition thinking,

00:42:44.020 --> 00:42:46.000
"I'm gonna get that mirror ball."

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:47.000
Or just.

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:48.000
Sorry.

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:49.000
What was your motivation?

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:50.000
[laughter]

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:51.000
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: My motivation?

00:42:51.000 --> 00:42:52.040
My motivation was really just learning how
to ballroom dance.

00:42:52.040 --> 00:42:58.000
'Cause I didn't wanna do the show because
having been a fan of the show, sitting around

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:00.430
with my girlfriends and ripping on all the
contestants--

00:43:00.430 --> 00:43:01.430
[laughter]

00:43:01.430 --> 00:43:06.119
I was like, "Oh, I don't wanna put myself
out there like that."

00:43:06.119 --> 00:43:09.930
But when I looked past that, I was like, "OK."

00:43:09.930 --> 00:43:15.130
I've always wanted to learn how to dance and
this type of dancing was so different from

00:43:15.130 --> 00:43:17.510
anything else I have ever done.

00:43:17.510 --> 00:43:18.630
I said, "OK.

00:43:18.630 --> 00:43:21.180
Just let's give it a shot."

00:43:21.180 --> 00:43:23.300
So, I don't know.

00:43:23.300 --> 00:43:24.300
I just went for it.

00:43:24.300 --> 00:43:25.300
[giggles]

00:43:25.300 --> 00:43:26.300
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Anyone else?

00:43:26.300 --> 00:43:27.300
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #10: Hey Kristi.

00:43:27.300 --> 00:43:28.300
Thanks for coming.

00:43:28.300 --> 00:43:29.300
Me and my sister we're also from Fremont.

00:43:29.300 --> 00:43:30.300
[laughter]

00:43:30.300 --> 00:43:33.170
&gt;&gt;Kristi Yamaguchi: Fremont hands go up.

00:43:33.170 --> 00:43:37.930
How many people are there from Fremont?

00:43:37.930 --> 00:43:39.570
Oh my goodness.

00:43:39.570 --> 00:43:41.340
Look at that.

